03959nam a22005775i 9780231558242DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022045547  a97802315582427 a10.7312/kile210042doi  a(DE-B1597)653706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2698.L52bZ726 2023 7aLIT0080102bisacsh1 aKile, S. E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTowers in the Void :bLi Yu and Early Modern Chinese Media /cS. E. Kile. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b18 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tConventions -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE Textual Media -- tPART TWO Spatial Media -- tPART THREE Corporeal Media -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: Li Yu’s Oeuvre -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe maverick cultural entrepreneur Li Yu survived the tumultuous Ming-Qing dynastic transition of the mid-seventeenth century through a commercially successful practice founded on intermedial experimentation. He engaged an astonishingly broad variety of cultural forms: from theatrical performance and literary production to fashion and wellness; from garden and interior design to the composition of letters and administrative documents. Drawing on his nonliterary work to reshape his writing, he translated this wide-ranging expertise into easily transmittable woodblock-printed form. Towers in the Void is a groundbreaking analysis of Li Yu’s work across these varied fields. It uses the concept of media to traverse them, revealing Li Yu’s creative enterprise as a remaking of early modern media forms.S. E. Kile argues that Li Yu’s cultural experimentation exploits the seams between language and the tangible world. He draws attention to the materiality of particular media forms, expanding the scope of early modern media by interweaving books, buildings, and bodies. Within and across these media, Li Yu’s cultural entrepreneurship with the technology of the printed book embraced its reproducibility while retaining a personal touch. His literary practice informed his garden design and, conversely, he drew on garden design to transform the vernacular short story. Ideas for extreme body modification in Li Yu’s fiction remade the possibilities of real human bodies in his nonfiction writing. Towers in the Void calls for seeing books, bodies, and buildings as interlinked media forms, both in early modern China and in today’s media-saturated world, positioning the Ming and Qing as a crucial site of global early modern cultural change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kile2100440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231558242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231558242/original  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK